---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import { Code } from "astro:components";---

<DocsLayout title="Quick Start">
  <h1>Quick Start</h1>
  <p>Build a task management system in 5 minutes using the proto-first workflow.</p>

  <h2>1. Define Your Schema in .proto</h2>
  <p>
    Create <code>schema.proto</code>. Every message that becomes a node gets a
    stable <code>type_id</code>; every field uses its protobuf field number as
    the on-disk <code>field_id</code>. Renames are free &mdash; only IDs are
    load-bearing.
  </p>
  <Code code={`// schema.proto
syntax = "proto3";
package myapp;

import "entdb/options.proto";

message User {
  option (entdb.type_id) = 10;
  string email = 1;
  string name = 2;
}

message Task {
  option (entdb.type_id) = 1;
  string title = 1;
  string status = 2;    // "todo" | "in_progress" | "done"
  int32 priority = 3;
}

message Comment {
  option (entdb.type_id) = 3;
  string body = 1;
}`} lang="proto" />

  <h2>2. Compile with protoc</h2>
  <p>
    Use the standard protobuf compiler &mdash; no EntDB-specific codegen.
  </p>
  <Code code={`protoc --python_out=. schema.proto
# produces schema_pb2.py`} lang="bash" />

  <h2>3. Register the Schema &amp; Connect</h2>
  <Code code={`import asyncio
from entdb_sdk import DbClient, Actor, Permission, register_proto_schema
import schema_pb2

registry = register_proto_schema(schema_pb2)

async def main():
    async with DbClient("localhost:50051", registry=registry) as db:
        scope = db.tenant("acme").actor(Actor.user("alice"))

        # Create a task with a comment, atomically
        plan = scope.plan()
        plan.create(schema_pb2.Task(title="Ship v2", status="todo"), as_="task")
        plan.create(schema_pb2.Comment(body="Let's ship it!"), as_="comment")
        plan.edge_create("HasComment", from_="$task.id", to="$comment.id")
        result = await plan.commit(wait_applied=True)

        task_id = result.created_node_ids[0]
        print(f"Created task: {task_id}")

        # Query tasks — read-after-write is automatic
        tasks = await scope.query(schema_pb2.Task,
                                  filter={"status": "todo"}, limit=10)
        for t in tasks:
            print(f"  {t.node_id}: {t.payload['title']}")

asyncio.run(main())`} lang="python" />

  <h2>4. Share a Task</h2>
  <p>
    Permissions use the <code>Permission</code> enum and actors are typed.
    Edges marked <code>propagate_share=True</code> (e.g. <code>HasComment</code>)
    mean the comment inherits the task's ACL automatically.
  </p>
  <Code code={`async def share_task(db, task_id):
    alice = db.tenant("acme").actor(Actor.user("alice"))
    await alice.share(task_id, Actor.user("bob"), Permission.WRITE)

    # Bob can see the task and all its comments
    bob = db.tenant("acme").actor(Actor.user("bob"))
    comments = await bob.connected(task_id, "HasComment")
    print(f"Bob sees {len(comments)} comments")`} lang="python" />

  <h2>5. Update Data</h2>
  <Code code={`async def update_task(db, task_id):
    scope = db.tenant("acme").actor(Actor.user("alice"))
    plan = scope.plan()
    plan.update(schema_pb2.Task, task_id, {"status": "in_progress"})
    await plan.commit()`} lang="python" />

  <h2>6. Add a Field Later (Non-Breaking)</h2>
  <p>
    Add a new field in <code>schema.proto</code> with a fresh field number.
    Because EntDB stores payloads keyed by <code>field_id</code>, you can
    even rename existing fields freely.
  </p>
  <Code code={`message Task {
  option (entdb.type_id) = 1;
  string title = 1;
  string status = 2;
  int32 priority = 3;
  int64 due_date = 4;   // NEW field — field_id 4
}`} lang="proto" />
  <Code code={`$ protoc --python_out=. schema.proto
$ entdb check         # validates compatibility vs the baseline snapshot
Schema compatible: 1 non-breaking change (field added)
$ entdb snapshot --update`} lang="bash" />

